Chapter 2: Build the Living Archive
Core Question
Where will the society’s memory live?
Understand
An archive should not be a dead folder.
It should be a living structure that future members can use.
The archive should help someone understand:
What the society is
 Why it exists
 How it works
 What it has done
 What it has learned
 What rules govern it
 What reports prove it
 What stories guide it
 What leaders carried it
 What responsibilities remain
A living archive should include:
Purpose
 Covenant
 Rules
 Meeting notes
 Treasury summaries
 Ledger snapshots
 Day 100 Reports
 Next Container Reports
 Institution Reports
 Ecosystem Reports
 Wealth Circulation Reports
 Property Reports
 Federation Reports
 Civic Power Reports
 Photos with consent
 Oral histories with consent
 Elder interviews
 Youth projects
 Business campaigns
 Property stewardship records
 Training materials
 Role descriptions
 Procedures
 Conflict repair lessons
 Partnership agreements
 Public testimony
 Media coverage
 Annual reflections
An archive protects the society from beginning again from zero.
Discuss
Where are our records now?
What is scattered?
What should be private?
What can be shared with members?
What can be public?
Who will maintain the archive?
Who will train the next archive keeper?
