Chapter 3: Record the Founding Story
Core Question
How did this society begin, and why did it matter?
Understand
Every institution needs a founding story.
Not a myth.
A truthful story.
The founding story should explain:
What problem made the society necessary
 Who gathered first
 What the early meetings were like
 What the first purpose was
 What the first contribution rhythm was
 What the first action was
 What almost stopped the work
 What helped people return
 What the society learned about trust
 What the society wants future members to protect
The founding story should not make heroes into idols.
It should show that ordinary people built structure.
A good founding story gives future members humility and responsibility.
It tells them:
This did not appear by magic.
People gathered.
People decided.
People contributed.
People recorded.
People repaired.
People returned.
Now you are responsible too.
Discuss
What problem brought us together?
Who called the first conversation?
Who showed up?
What did we decide first?
What was difficult?
What surprised us?
What should future members know about the beginning?
Build: Founding Story Worksheet
This society began because:

The first people who gathered were:

The recurring problem we wanted to address was:

Our first purpose was:

Our first action was:

The hardest early challenge was:

The first sign of trust was:

The first lesson we learned was:

What future members must remember:

