PART TWO: TEACH THE BLUEPRINT

Chapter 4: Create the Society Curriculum
Core Question
What must every future member learn?
Understand
A society that cannot teach itself cannot reproduce itself.
Every new member should learn the society’s basic curriculum.
The curriculum does not need to be complicated.
It should teach:
The blueprint sequence
 The society’s purpose
 The covenant
 Membership expectations
 Contribution rhythm
 Treasury basics
 Ledger meaning
 Privacy and dignity
 Care team structure
 Rules and decision-making
 Conflict repair
 Meeting rhythm
 Reporting culture
 Business support principles
 Property stewardship principles
 Youth formation
 Preparedness
 History and decolonization
 Civic responsibility
 Succession
The curriculum should not be a lecture series only.
It should include practice.
Members should not just hear about the ledger.
They should understand why a clean ledger is a trust document.
They should not just hear about meetings.
They should learn how meetings produce decisions, assignments, records, and return.
They should not just hear about history.
They should see history as evidence and the blueprint as the product.
Discuss
What did we wish we knew when we started?
What must every member understand before voting or handling money?
What should supporters learn?
What should youth learn?
What should leaders learn?
What can be taught in 4 sessions?
