Chapter 6: Honor Elders as Memory Keepers
Core Question
How do we receive elder memory without extracting from elders?
Understand
Elders are not archives to be mined.
They are people to be honored.
Elder memory can teach:
How the community survived
 Who built institutions before
 What was lost
 What was protected
 What mistakes repeated
 What land meant
 What church, school, business, family, and neighborhood life carried
 What mutual aid looked like before the platform existed
 What younger people need to know
But elder memory must be received with consent, care, and dignity.
Do not pressure elders to share.
Do not publish stories without permission.
Do not ask for painful memory without support.
Do not separate stories from the people who lived them.
Elder memory should become guidance.
Not content.
Discuss
Which elders carry important memory?
What should we ask with care?
What should not be asked?
Who should conduct interviews?
What consent is needed?
How will the story be used?
How will the elder receive the finished record?
