Chapter 9: Practice Leadership Rotation
Core Question
Can leadership move without breaking the work?
Understand
Succession should be practiced before it is required.
A society can practice leadership rotation in small ways:
A new person facilitates one meeting.
A youth member reads the agenda.
An assistant treasurer presents the ledger summary.
A trainee recordkeeper takes notes.
A care team member leads a check-in.
A business liaison trainee gives the campaign report.
A property liaison trainee presents the records checklist.
A civic apprentice summarizes a public meeting.
Practice rotation helps the society learn where training is needed.
It also teaches members that leadership belongs to the institution, not one personality.
Discuss
What role can rotate safely first?
Who is ready to practice?
What support does the person need?
What could go wrong?
How will feedback be given?
What will we learn from the rotation?
Build: Leadership Rotation Practice
Role being practiced:

Person practicing:

Mentor/support person:

Practice date:

Preparation needed:

What authority is included?

What authority is not included?

Feedback method:

Review date:

