PART FOUR: CREATE GENERATIONAL PRACTICE

Chapter 11: Build the Annual Legacy Rhythm
Core Question
What should the society repeat every year so memory does not fade?
Understand
Legacy requires rhythm.
If memory is only preserved during crisis or anniversaries, it becomes fragile.
The society should create an annual rhythm for remembering, teaching, reporting, and recommitting.
Annual legacy practices may include:
Founding story reading
 Covenant renewal
 Elder memory session
 Youth report-back
 Ledger and treasury review
 Property records reminder
 Business circulation report
 Preparedness drill
 Institution maturity audit
 Leadership rotation review
 Succession plan update
 Archive day
 History lesson
 Community meal
 Day of service
 Public report
 Next generation blessing
Annual rhythm turns memory into practice.
The goal is not ceremony alone.
The goal is renewal.
Discuss
What should we repeat every year?
What season or date matters?
How do we include youth?
How do we honor elders?
What report should be presented?
What responsibility should be renewed?
Build: Annual Legacy Calendar
