Chapter 12: Create a Generational Covenant
Core Question
What promise do we pass forward?
Understand
The original covenant helped the first society hold together.
A generational covenant speaks across time.
It tells future members:
What must be protected
 What must be practiced
 What must be taught
 What must not be sold cheaply
 What must not be forgotten
 How to handle money
 How to handle conflict
 How to treat elders
 How to train youth
 How to protect property
 How to support businesses
 How to speak with dignity
 How to continue when founders are gone
A generational covenant should not trap future members.
It should give them roots.
They may adapt forms, tools, and strategies.
But they should understand the principles.
Discuss
What promise do we want future members to inherit?
What principle should never be abandoned?
What mistake should never be repeated?
What responsibility belongs to every generation?
What should future members be free to change?
Build: Generational Covenant
We received:

We protected:

We learned:

We commit to pass forward:

Future members must remember:

Future members may adapt:

Future members must never abandon:

Generational covenant statement:

Chapter Outputs
[ ] Generational covenant drafted
 [ ] Nonnegotiable principles named
 [ ] Adaptable practices named
 [ ] Future responsibility written
 [ ] Covenant saved in archive
Do in Simba
Use Covenant Builder, Society Archive, Youth Integration, and History Integration.

Chapter 13: Create the Builder-to-Builder Transfer
Core Question
How does one generation teach the next generation to build?
Understand
Legacy transfer should be practical.
Not only speeches.
A builder-to-builder transfer pairs experienced members with newer members or youth around real responsibilities.
Examples:
Treasurer teaches ledger review.
Recordkeeper teaches archive management.
Care Coordinator teaches care team setup.
Property Liaison teaches document checklists.
Business Liaison teaches buying campaign setup.
Preparedness Lead teaches communication tree planning.
Civic Lead teaches public meeting monitoring.
Elder Liaison teaches consent-based memory gathering.
Founder teaches purpose and covenant history.
The goal is not only to tell what happened.
The goal is to teach how to do the work.
Discuss
Who knows how to do something important?
Who needs to learn it?
What responsibility can be transferred in practice?
What output will prove learning happened?
How will the teacher know the learner is ready?
Build: Builder-to-Builder Transfer Plan
Skill/responsibility:

Current builder:

Next builder:

Practice task:

Materials needed:

Shadow date:

Independent practice date:

Review date:

Proof of readiness:

