Chapter 14: Protect the Story
Core Question
Who owns the story of what we built?
Understand
If a society becomes effective, others may want to tell its story.
Media.
Researchers.
Funders.
Politicians.
Partners.
Platforms.
Influencers.
Documentarians.
Even members.
Story can inspire.
Story can also extract.
The society should decide:
Who can speak for the society?
 What can be public?
 What requires consent?
 What stories are private?
 What images can be used?
 What youth protections apply?
 What elder protections apply?
 Who approves media?
 Who owns recordings?
 Who can use the society’s name?
 What must never be shared?
Narrative power is part of stewardship.
A society that does not protect its story may lose control of its meaning.
Discuss
What stories can be public?
What stories belong only to members?
What requires consent?
Who can speak publicly?
What should media never receive?
What public story do we want to tell?
Build: Story Protection Policy
Public spokespersons:

Stories that can be public:

Stories that require consent:

Stories that remain private:

Photo/video rule:

Youth media rule:

Elder story rule:

Research/media request process:

